 seems essential to solving the manifest problems of this highly politicized and emotionally charged aspect of American higher education. The research evidence presented in this book has a direct relevance to those court cases that challenge race-conscious admission policies of colleges and universities. Though many questions still need to be addressed by future research, the empirical data collected to date makes it clear that affirmative action policies do work and are still very much needed in American higher education. This book also provides a framework for examining the evidence pertaining to issues of fairness, merit, and the benefits of diversity in an effort to assist courts and the public in organizing beliefs about race and opportunity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAffirmative action programszUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in higher educationzUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationzUnited States. 4aEducation. 4aSociology -- Education and Society. 4aSociology -- Race, Class, and Gender. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh1 aChang, Mitchell J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChang, Mitchell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHakuta, Kenji, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHakuta, Kenji, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJones, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMilem, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShin, Clara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWightman, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWitt, Daria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWitt, Daria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vo